## Is the data enough for analysis?

Yes, for most fitness/health analysis. Some gaps exist.

| Metric | Coverage | Verdict |
|---|---|---|
| Steps | 273/290 days (94%) | ✅ Excellent — daily trends, weekly patterns, streak analysis |
| Distance | 268/290 days (92%) | ✅ Excellent — correlates well with steps |
| Heart Rate | 130K samples, 65% days | ✅ Good — dense on active days (avg 693 samples/day) |
| Sleep sessions | 144/289 days (50%) | ⚠️ Moderate — missing ~half the nights, likely unworn watch |
| Sleep stages | 4,205 segments, 51% | ⚠️ Same gap — but rich detail where recorded (deep/REM/light breakdown) |
| Exercise | 199 sessions, 3 types | ✅ Good — ~1 session every 1.5 days over 9+ months |
| Resting HR | 133/278 days (48%) | ⚠️ Moderate — enough for trend/fitness level analysis |
| Weight | 44 entries (15%) | ❌ Sparse — only occasional weigh-ins, unreliable for trend |

What you can confidently analyse:
- Daily activity patterns and streaks (steps, distance)
- Heart rate zones during exercise
- Sleep quality and stage distribution on nights you wore the device
- Exercise frequency and load over 9 months
- Fitness level trend via resting HR (where available)

What you can't reliably do:
- Weight trend analysis (too few points)
- Sleep consistency analysis (50% missing nights skew any averages)
- Calorie balance (no nutrition data at all)

Span: ~9.5 months (Sep 2025 – Jun 2026) — solid for longitudinal trend analysis.

